<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How does a love compatibility calculator work?", answer: "Most online love calculators use name numerology — they assign each letter a number (A=1, B=2, ..., Z=26), sum the values for both names, and run a simple formula on the total to produce a percentage. It is a fun, lighthearted tool, not a scientific measure of relationship success. Think of it as a conversation starter or a shareable result, not a recommendation about who to date." },
  { question: "Is the love calculator scientifically accurate?", answer: "No. Love compatibility cannot be reduced to letters in a name. Decades of research from the Gottman Institute and others show that real relationship success depends on shared values, communication style, conflict resolution, and commitment — none of which a name can predict. Use this calculator for fun and the occasional ice-breaker. For serious assessment, look at attachment style, love languages, and relationship readiness instead." },
  { question: "Why do I keep getting different scores for similar names?", answer: "Small letter changes (Mike vs Michael, Liz vs Elizabeth) shift the letter sum by a meaningful amount, which changes the percentage by 5–20 points. That is by design — the formula amplifies small differences so the results feel responsive instead of always landing in the same range. Try the full names and the nicknames to see which one you like better." },
  { question: "Can a low score mean we should not date?", answer: "Absolutely not. A low love calculator score means literally nothing about your real relationship. Couples who score 30% on these tools have been married for 50 years; couples who score 99% have broken up after a month. The calculator is for fun. If you have doubts about your relationship, talk to your partner — or a therapist — not a name calculator." },
  { question: "How can I improve my love compatibility?", answer: "Real compatibility grows through shared experiences, vulnerability, and mutual effort. Date regularly, communicate openly, learn each other's love languages, and handle conflict with curiosity instead of contempt. Couples who report the highest satisfaction tend to do small acts of kindness daily, share humor, and maintain individual identities alongside the relationship." }
]) %>

